ce:section.ce:para:
Given the above-described challenges, the nitrated CDs nanoparticles were designed to reveal the GSH sensitive NO release and in-situ conversion for highly efficient gas therapy and phototherapy (Scheme 1
                     ). Herein, CDs were synthesized by using methylene blue (MB) as carbon source via hydrothermal strategy (Fig. 1
                     A). The as-synthesized CDs possess great adsorption in NIR-II region. The deeper tissue penetration (3–5 cm) and higher permissible exposure (1 W cm−2) endows NIR-II light with great advantages in cancer treatment [36]. In addition, CDs reveal novel performance on NIR-II triggered hyperpyrexia and ROS generation for phototherapy. On account of the hydrothermal process, plenty of –OH groups remain on the surface of CDs. And then, a simple nitration reaction was carried out to induce nitrated CDs (CDs-NO), which can release NO in the presence of GSH. GSH, a typical endogenous reluctant enzyme, is abundant in tumor microenvironment (TME, about 7–10 times higher than that of normal tissues) that endows CDs-NO with tumor-targeted NO release. Moreover, the consumption of GSH also can alleviate antioxidant defense in TME, benefiting to the elevation of oxidative stress for PDT. In addition, the effect of NO on angiectasis and hypoxia relief also is investigated. Under NIR-II irradiation, the in-situ generation of ROS could capture NO to form ONOO− radical fast, elevating cytotoxicity and half-life. The synergistic phototherapy and NO therapy exhibit significant therapeutic effect on tumor (4T1) bearing mice. Besides, it also arouses immune response to inhibit metastasis efficiently.
